            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born in Tehran in 1970, Arash Rostami\u2019s early life was framed by the poetry of Hafez and the tremors of revolution. His parents, a civil engineer and a literature professor, saw the world they knew dissolving and instilled in their son a singular focus: education was the only portable, unassailable wealth. Arash found his refuge in the elegant certainty of numbers, a stark contrast to the political chaos outside his window. After excelling in his studies, he seized the opportunity to leave Iran, arriving at UC Berkeley in the early 1990s to pursue a graduate degree in Statistics. The transition was jarring but liberating, trading the weight of history for the promise of innovation.\n\nArash\u2019s career began during the dot-com boom, but he sidestepped the frenetic startup culture, preferring the methodical work of established firms. He patiently built his expertise, earning a reputation for his calm demeanor and his almost preternatural ability to find signals in noisy data. Now a Principal Data Scientist, he leads a team at a major tech firm, mentoring a new generation of analysts. His greatest professional satisfaction comes from solving a seemingly intractable problem, a quiet thrill that reminds him why he fell in love with logic in the first place.\n\nHe met his wife, Elham, a graphic designer, at a gathering for Iranian expatriates. They built a life together, raising a daughter who is now studying premed at UCLA. Their home in Cole Valley is a sanctuary of calm, filled with books, Persian art, and the aroma of saffron rice. Arash\u2019s daily routine is structured: a morning walk with their dog in the Presidio, the company shuttle ride where he reads academic papers, and an intense day of work, followed by a quiet evening with Elham.\n\nSan Francisco, for Arash, is the fulfillment of a promise. He values its intellectual vigor and the freedom to be unapologetically himself. He has achieved the stability his parents dreamed for him, but he isn't complacent. He aspires to use his expertise for social good, perhaps consulting for a nonprofit focused on refugee resettlement. He dreams of seeing his daughter thrive and, one day, taking a long trip along the Silk Road\u2014not to reclaim a lost past, but to appreciate the long, winding path that brought him here."
