craved most: a world where learning was a game, not an escape.\n\n5.\nJust last autumn, on his morning walk in the Presidio. The fog was pulling back from the Golden Gate Bridge, revealing its impossible, rust-colored strength. He thought of his father, the builder of solid things, and the turbulent history he had crossed to be here. With his dog sniffing at the cypress trees and the city humming behind him, he felt a quiet, unshakable peace. This wasn't a refuge from the world, but his place in it. The promise had been fulfilled."
